dren became the victims. It thus became the province of the courts to reinforce the cultural value of marriage by resisting what came to be known as the “procreation argument,” the assertion that marriage exists primarily to regulate the unruly aspects of heterosexual reproduction. Cultural conceptions of children and childhood were being put at risk as gays and lesbians were denied marriage, so that writing lesbian and gay families into the marriage law became the better option.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChildren and sex. 0aMarriagexSocial aspects. 0aSame-sex marriagexLaw and legislationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSame-sex marriagexSocial aspects. 0aSex and lawzUnited States. 0aSexxSocial aspects. 0aSociological jurisprudencezUnited States. 7aLAW / Family Law / Marriage.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072897240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479812585423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479812585.jpg  a978-3-11-072897-2  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK